The start symbol S expands as:  
S → NT56 NT45  

NT45 has exactly one production:  
NT45 → 't4'  

Therefore any string derived from S must end with the single terminal t4 (the part generated by NT45).  
The given string ends with t20, and nowhere in the string does the token t4 appear.  

Hence the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

The start symbol S always expands as:
S → NT56 NT45

In Chomsky normal form, NT45 can only derive a single terminal.  
The grammar contains exactly one lexical rule for NT45:

NT45 → 't4'

Hence every string generated by the grammar must end with the token t4.

The given string ends with t29, not t4:

… t29   (last token)

Therefore the string cannot be derived from S, and so it is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The only production for the start symbol is  
S → NT56 NT45.

NT45 appears nowhere on the left–hand side of any other rule except this one, and its only production is the terminal rule  

NT45 → 't4'.

Therefore every string generated from S must end with the single terminal t4.

The given string ends with t0, not t4, and in fact contains no t4 at all. Consequently the grammar cannot generate the provided string.

No

To derive the string we would have to use the only start-production  

S → NT56 NT45  

because S has no other rule.

1. NT45 can only produce the terminal t4 (there are no other productions for NT45).  
   Hence the last symbol of any sentence derived from the grammar is t4 – this
   agrees with the given string.

2. So the prefix of length 17 must be generated by NT56.
   NT56, however, has only two possibilities:

   a) NT56 → 't33'  (produces exactly one token, t33)  
   b) NT56 → NT69 NT44

   Case (a) cannot yield 17 tokens.

3. For case (b) we need to inspect NT69.

   • NT69 → 't5'   (produces the single token t5)  
   • NT69 → NT63 NT49 → 't9' 't15' (produces the two tokens t9 t15)

   Therefore every string generated by NT69 begins with either t5 or
   the pair t9 t15.

   Consequently every string generated by NT56 begins with
   t5 …  or t9 t15 … , because the symbols of NT69 come first.

4. The given string begins with t9 t9 … , which is incompatible with both
   possibilities above (it is neither t5 … nor t9 t15 …).

Hence NT56 cannot generate the required 17-token prefix, and therefore
S cannot generate the full 18-token string.

Answer: No

In every derivation from the start symbol we must begin with the rule  

S → NT56 NT45, where NT45 immediately produces the terminal t4 (it is the only production for NT45).  
Therefore the very last symbol of any string generated by the grammar is forced to be t4 – which is true for the given string.

The other non-terminal, NT56, has only two possibilities:

1. NT56 → 't33'  (produces the single terminal t33)  
2. NT56 → NT69 NT44

The string contains 40 terminals before the final t4, so the first alternative is impossible (it would give only one symbol).  
Consequently we must use the second alternative and the very first part of the string must be generated by NT69.

But NT69 itself has only these productions:

NT69 → 't5'  
NT69 → NT63 NT49 with NT63 → 't9' and NT49 → 't15'  
So NT69 can generate either  

• the single terminal t5, or  
• the two-terminal sequence t9 t15.

Hence every string derived from the grammar must start either with t5 … or with t9 t15 … .

The given string, however, begins with t9 t9 … , which matches neither possibility.

Therefore the string cannot be produced by the grammar.
